Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

A person makes a doctor appointment, receives all the instructions and no-show. Who to blame?

Content¶

110.527 medical appointments and its 14 associated variables (characteristics). The most important one if the patient show-up or no-show to the appointment. Variable names are self-explanatory.

Data Dictionary¶

1 - PatientId

Identification of a patient.

2 - AppointmentID

Identification of each appointment.

3 - Gender

Male or Female . Female is the greater proportion, woman takes way more care of they health in comparison to man.

4 - ScheduledDay

The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.

5 - AppointmentDay

The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.

6 - Age

How old is the patient.

7 - Neighbourhood

Where the appointment takes place.

8 - Scholarship

Indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família.

9 - Hipertension

True or False.

10 - Diabetes

True or False.

11 - Alcoholism

True or False.

12 - Handcap

True or False.

13 - SMS_received

1 or more messages sent to the patient.

14 - No-show

Yes or No.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

Why do patients miss their scheduled appointments? What variable(s) might affect the propabelity of them showing-up for their scheduled appointment?

# making a function to plot a histogram for each group against 1 variable
def hist_1d(df, col_name, title= None, xlabel= None, ylabel=None):
    plt.figure(figsize= (15,6))
    df[col_name][no_show].hist(alpha=0.7, label= 'No show');
    df[col_name][show].hist(alpha=0.7, label= 'Show');
    
    # title and labels
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 20)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel,fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize = 15)
    
    # legend
    plt.legend();
In [20]:
# making a function to plot a bar chart of the proportion of each group against 1 variable
def plot_proportions(df, col_name, width, title= None, xlabel= None, ylabel=None):
    counts = df.groupby(['No_show', col_name]).count()['Age']
    total_counts = df.groupby('No_show').count()['Age']
    show_proportions = counts['Yes'] / total_counts['Yes']
    no_show_proportions = counts['No'] / total_counts['No']
    ind = np.arange(len(no_show_proportions))
    

    # plot bars
    plt.figure(figsize= (15,6))
    no_show_bars = plt.bar(ind, no_show_proportions, width, alpha=.7, label='No show')
    show_bars = plt.bar(ind + width, show_proportions, width, alpha=.7, label='Show')

    # title and labels
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 20)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel,fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize = 15)
    plt.grid(visible= True);
    locations = ind + width / 2  # xtick locations
    labels = df[col_name].unique()  # xtick labels
    plt.xticks(locations, labels)

    # legend
    plt.legend();

Does Age and Gender affect attendance together?¶

In [29]:
# making a function to plot a bar chart for each group against 2 variables
def bar_2d(df, x_col_name, y_col_name, title= None, xlabel= None, ylabel=None):
    plt.figure(figsize= (15,6))
    df[no_show].groupby(x_col_name)[y_col_name].mean().plot(kind='bar', color='blue', alpha=.6, label= 'No show');
    df[show].groupby(x_col_name)[y_col_name].mean().plot(kind='bar', color='orange', alpha=.6, label= 'show');
    
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 20)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel,fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize = 15)
    plt.legend();
    plt.grid(visible=True);
In [30]:
bar_2d(df, 'Gender', 'Age',  'Relationship between gender and mean age', 'Gender', 'Mean age')

Conclusions¶

  • Patients who didn't receive SMS and didn't show-up were 40% more than patients who did receive it. This means we need to broaden the scope of our SMS campaign in order to reach more patients.
  • Age has a great influence on attendance. Patients aged 11–22 have the highest ratio of shows to no-shows and patients over 65 have the lowest number of shows in our samble.
  • Neighbourhood has a remarkable effect on patients' showing-up. Each neighbourhood has its own unique behaviour - in terms of patients count and thier mean age - that needs to be further investigated.

Limitations¶

  • There is no clear relationship between patients showing and Gender, Chronic Diseases and having Bolsa Família scholarship.
  • The number of patients suffering from alcoholism is too small to be invstigated.
